</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div class="core-first-page-image"><img alt="First page of PDF" src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/rg.281075092.fp.png_v03" loading="lazy" /></div></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.281075092">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.281075092">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33g01x.jpeg" height="1036" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Abdominal US image demonstrates a large heterogeneous mass with a “pseudokidney” appearance. Central hyperechoic material (thick arrow) represents mesenteric fat within the intussuscipiens, which has a hypoechoic wall (thin arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33g02a.jpeg" height="1165" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image oriented parallel to the longitudinal plane of the intussusception demonstrates a heterogeneous “sausage” mass with central low-attenuation fat (arrow), which is being dragged into the intussuscipiens by the intussusceptum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image clearly demonstrates the intussuscipiens (thick white arrow), intussusceptum (thin white arrow), and vessels (black arrows) within the invaginated mesenteric fat. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT reformatted image depicts the large intussusception mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33g02b.jpeg" height="1057" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image oriented parallel to the longitudinal plane of the intussusception demonstrates a heterogeneous “sausage” mass with central low-attenuation fat (arrow), which is being dragged into the intussuscipiens by the intussusceptum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image clearly demonstrates the intussuscipiens (thick white arrow), intussusceptum (thin white arrow), and vessels (black arrows) within the invaginated mesenteric fat. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT reformatted image depicts the large intussusception mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33g02c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1374" aria-labelledby="F2C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2c.</b>  <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image oriented parallel to the longitudinal plane of the intussusception demonstrates a heterogeneous “sausage” mass with central low-attenuation fat (arrow), which is being dragged into the intussuscipiens by the intussusceptum. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image clearly demonstrates the intussuscipiens (thick white arrow), intussusceptum (thin white arrow), and vessels (black arrows) within the invaginated mesenteric fat. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT reformatted image depicts the large intussusception mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F2C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33c03x.jpeg" height="957" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3.</b>  Intraoperative photograph shows the transition zone of the intussusception, which was caused by a lead-point Peutz-Jeghers polyp. The intussusceptum (thick arrow) is dilating and obstructing the intussuscipiens (thin arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33c04x.jpeg" height="1016" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4.</b>  Photograph of the gross bowel specimen demonstrates the lead-point polyp (thick arrow) with several smaller polyps aggregated at the base of the dominant polyp (thin arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33c05x.jpeg" height="922" width="757" aria-labelledby="F5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5.</b>  Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; hematoxylin-eosin stain) demonstrates that Peutz-Jeghers polyps characteristically contain a core of arborizing smooth muscle (thick arrow), upon which rests mucosa that is native to the site of the polyp, in this case small bowel mucosa. Note that although the surface is hemorrhagic (thin arrow), in other areas the surface is entirely necrotic.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.281075092/asset/images/g08ja33c06x.jpeg" height="675" width="1215" aria-labelledby="F6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6.</b>  Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×100; hematoxylin-eosin stain) shows that this large Peutz-Jeghers polyp includes nests of benign mucosa (arrows) that are located in the submucosa and muscularis propria, which is called epithelial misplacement or “pseudoinvasion.” This is a relatively uncommon but well-described finding in Peutz-Jeghers polyps and should not be mistaken for invasive carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.281075092&amp;id=F6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="